// Image List for Chapter 4: DNA, Chromosomes, and Genomes

- Figure 4-1: Chromosomes in cells — light micrograph of two adjacent plant cells showing DNA stained with DAPI; one cell displays compact, sausage-shaped chromosomes prior to division, illustrating the condensed versus extended states of chromatin.
- Figure 4-2: The first experimental demonstration that DNA is the genetic material — the Griffith/Avery transformation experiments showing that purified DNA from pathogenic S-strain bacteria can transform nonpathogenic R-strain bacteria, identifying DNA as the hereditary molecule.
- Figure 4-3: DNA and its four nucleotide building blocks — schematic diagrams showing (A) a single nucleotide, (B) a polynucleotide chain, (C) double-stranded DNA held by hydrogen bonds, and (D) the DNA double helix, illustrating how the 5'→3' antiparallel strands form the helical structure.
- Figure 4-4: The nucleotide subunits within a DNA strand are held together by a phosphodiester bond — detailed chemical structure showing the covalent linkage between the 3'-hydroxyl of one sugar and the 5'-phosphate of the next, giving the strand chemical polarity.
- Figure 4-5: How the two strands of the DNA double helix are held together by hydrogen bonds between complementary base pairs — structural diagrams showing (A) two hydrogen bonds between A–T and three between G–C, and (B) a short section of the double helix viewed from the side with base pairs perpendicular to the helix axis.
- Figure 4-6: A space-filling model of the DNA double helix — atomic-resolution model showing the right-handed helix, major groove, minor groove, sugar–phosphate backbone on the outside, and bases stacked on the inside; one complete turn every 10.4 base pairs.
- Figure 4-7: DNA as a template for its own duplication — diagram illustrating semiconservative replication, where each parental strand serves as a template to produce two identical daughter double helices, explaining the hereditary transmission of genetic information.
- Figure 4-8: Most genes contain information to make proteins — schematic showing the central dogma: DNA genes (A, B, C, D) are transcribed into RNA, then translated into proteins; gene C illustrates an RNA-only gene product.
- Figure 4-9: The nucleotide sequence of the human β-globin gene — a written-out 5'→3' nucleotide sequence of the entire β-globin gene, with the three protein-coding exons highlighted in yellow, illustrating that most of the gene consists of non-coding introns.
- Figure 4-10: A cross-sectional view of a typical cell nucleus — electron micrograph and schematic of a human fibroblast nucleus showing the double nuclear envelope, nuclear pores, nuclear lamina, endoplasmic reticulum continuity, nucleolus, and heterochromatin regions.
- Figure 4-11: The complete set of human chromosomes — spectral karyotype of a female cell where each chromosome is painted a different color by fluorescent DNA probes; shows (A) chromosomes spilling from a lysed cell and (B) the 46 chromosomes arranged into the standard karyotype.
- Figure 4-12: The banding patterns of human mitotic chromosomes — G-banding pattern of all 46 human chromosomes showing the unique, reproducible alternating dark and light bands used to identify and number each chromosome.
- Figure 4-13: Aberrant human chromosomes — chromosome painting revealing translocations and deletions: (A) normal chromosomes 4 and 6; (B) and (C) rearranged versions, demonstrating how chromosome painting detects structural abnormalities linked to inherited disease and cancer.
- Figure 4-14: Two closely related Drosophila species that differ in chromosome number — illustrating that genome rearrangements (including chromosome fusions) can change chromosome number during evolution without necessarily changing gene content.
- Figure 4-15: The organization of genes on chromosomes — diagram of a eukaryotic gene showing the alternating arrangement of exons (protein-coding) and introns (non-coding), plus upstream and downstream regulatory sequences, illustrating that human genes average ~26,000 bp yet only ~1300 bp encode protein.
- Figure 4-16: Scale of some human genome features — a visual scale comparison: if 1 mm = 1 base pair, the human genome would stretch 3,100 km; an average gene would span 26 meters, but its coding sequence only ~1 meter, conveying the vast non-coding content.
- Table 4-1: The nucleotide sequence content of the human genome — table summarizing the composition of the 3.1-billion-bp human genome: ~1% protein-coding exons, ~25% introns, ~15% regulatory and other functional sequences, ~45% transposable element remnants, and ~15% other non-repetitive DNA.
- Figure 4-17: A simplified view of the eukaryotic cell cycle — diagram contrasting interphase (gene expression, chromosome duplication, extended chromatin) with M phase (chromosome condensation, mitotic spindle formation, sister chromatid separation, cell division).
- Figure 4-18: A mitotic chromosome — electron micrograph and schematic of a metaphase chromosome showing its two sister chromatids joined at the centromere constriction; illustrates the highly compacted state chromosomes adopt for segregation.
- Figure 4-19: The three specialized sites on chromosomal DNA required for chromosome replication and segregation — diagram showing (1) replication origins where duplication initiates, (2) the centromere where the kinetochore forms for spindle attachment, and (3) telomeres that protect and replicate chromosome ends.
- Figure 4-20: Chromatin — diagram illustrating that chromatin consists of approximately one-third DNA, one-third histones, and one-third non-histone proteins by mass; it is a complex of DNA and protein that makes up chromosomes.
- Figure 4-21: Nucleosomes as seen in the electron microscope — electron micrograph of chromatin released from a nucleus showing the "beads-on-a-string" appearance; each bead is a nucleosome (~10 nm diameter) spaced at ~200-bp intervals along the DNA strand.
- Figure 4-22: Structural organization of the nucleosome — diagram showing how 147 bp of DNA wraps ~1.65 times around the histone octamer (two copies each of H2A, H2B, H3, and H4), with ~50 bp of linker DNA between nucleosomes.
- Figure 4-23: The structure of a nucleosome core particle — high-resolution X-ray crystal structure showing the disk-shaped histone octamer core, the left-handed superhelical wrapping of DNA, and the protruding N-terminal histone tails.
- Figure 4-24: The overall structural organization of the nucleosome — detailed view of the histone fold motifs of the four core histones and the eight-subunit octamer; highlights the H3–H4 tetramer core flanked by two H2A–H2B dimers.
- Figure 4-25: The bending of DNA in a nucleosome — showing that DNA is bent more sharply in certain positions due to sequence-dependent flexibility; A–T-rich sequences are easier to bend, explaining some positional preferences of nucleosomes.
- Figure 4-26: The nucleosome movements catalyzed by ATP-dependent chromatin-remodeling complexes — (A) mechanism of nucleosome sliding: the remodeling complex uses ATP hydrolysis to translocate DNA relative to the histone core, one base pair per cycle; (B) structure of the yeast SWR1 complex that exchanges H2A–H2B dimers.
- Figure 4-27: Nucleosome removal and histone exchange — diagram showing two types of remodeling: (1) selective exchange of H2A–H2B dimers for variant histones (e.g., H2A.Z) and (2) complete removal of the histone octamer, exposing underlying DNA for transcription.
- Figure 4-28: A zigzag model for the chromatin fiber — X-ray crystallography structure of a tetranucleosome and schematic showing how nucleosomes stack into a higher-order zigzag array through internucleosomal contacts, producing a more compact chromatin fiber.
- Figure 4-29: A model for the role played by histone tails in the compaction of chromatin — (A) structure showing the eight N-terminal histone tails protruding from the nucleosome; (B) proposed internucleosomal interactions mediated by the H4 tail promoting chromatin compaction.
- Figure 4-30: How the linker histone H1 binds to the nucleosome — schematic and cryo-EM structure showing H1 contacting the nucleosome at the DNA entry/exit point, changing the DNA path and further compacting the chromatin fiber.
- Figure 4-31: Some distinct ways that DNA is packaged in chromatin in a mammalian cell — pie chart and diagram classifying ~80% of the human genome as closed/inactive chromatin (heterochromatin: constitutive and facultative) and ~20% as open/active euchromatin, with the histone marks H3K9me3 and H3K27me3 distinguishing the heterochromatin types.
- Figure 4-32: The cause of position effect variegation in Drosophila — diagram illustrating how a chromosome rearrangement places the White gene near heterochromatin, allowing heterochromatin to spread into the euchromatic region during development; different cells silence the gene to different extents, creating clonal patches in the eye.
- Figure 4-33: The discovery of position effects on gene expression — photographs of Drosophila eyes showing wild-type (all red), White-mutant (all white), and position-effect variegated (mottled red and white) eyes, demonstrating that chromatin state, not DNA mutation, determines gene activity in some cells.
- Figure 4-34: Some prominent types of covalent amino acid side-chain modifications found on nucleosomal histones — chemical structures showing (A) the three levels of lysine methylation (mono-, di-, trimethyl), with each recognized differently by reader proteins; acetylation removes the positive charge and blocks methylation; (B) serine phosphorylation adds negative charge.
- Figure 4-35: The covalent modification of core histones — (A) nucleosome structure highlighting the N-terminal tails; (B) map of well-documented modifications (acetylation, methylation, phosphorylation, ubiquitylation) on all four core histones H2A, H2B, H3, and H4, showing their positions within the tail and globular domains.
- Figure 4-36: The structure of some histone variants — structures of variant histones (e.g., H2A.Z, H3.3, CENP-A) compared to canonical histones, showing how amino acid differences produce distinct surfaces that affect nucleosome stability and recruit specific binding proteins.
- Figure 4-37: How a mark on a nucleosome can be read and transmitted — model showing a reader–writer complex: a reader domain recognizes a specific histone modification, while the associated writer enzyme places the same mark on adjacent nucleosomes, enabling spreading of a chromatin state along the chromosome.
- Figure 4-38: Schematic diagram showing how distinct chromatin domains are established and maintained — illustrating barrier sequences that prevent heterochromatin spreading into euchromatin domains, and how specific transcription factors establish boundaries.
- Figure 4-39: How the recruitment of reader–writer complexes can spread chromatin structure along a chromosome — step-by-step diagram showing: (1) initial recruitment by a sequence-specific DNA-binding protein, (2) spreading of the histone mark by reader–writer complexes to neighboring nucleosomes, forming a large heterochromatic domain.
- Figure 4-40: Two different processes that spread heterochromatin — comparison of H3K9me3 heterochromatin spreading (via HP1 recruitment and H3K9 methyltransferase) and H3K27me3 heterochromatin spreading (via Polycomb Repressive Complexes PRC1 and PRC2).
- Figure 4-41: Some mechanisms of epigenetic inheritance — overview of epigenetic memory mechanisms including DNA methylation of CpG islands, histone modification propagation, and chromatin remodeling, illustrating how gene expression states are inherited through cell divisions without changes in DNA sequence.
- Figure 4-42: The structure of a centromere — electron micrograph and diagram of a human centromere showing the kinetochore assembly on alpha-satellite DNA arrays with CENP-A–containing nucleosomes, and the attachment of microtubule fibers from the mitotic spindle.
- Figure 4-43: Evidence for the plasticity of human centromere formation — (A) series of alpha-satellite DNA arrays on chromosome 17 showing that large arrays do not always form centromeres; (B) a neocentromere forming on non-satellite DNA, showing that centromere identity is defined epigenetically by CENP-A rather than solely by DNA sequence.
- Figure 4-44: The propagation of heterochromatin across generations — diagram showing that after DNA replication, the old H3–H4 tetramers with H3K9me3 or H3K27me3 marks are distributed equally to both daughter chromatids; reader–writer complexes then mark the new nucleosomes on each daughter, faithfully propagating the heterochromatic state.
- Figure 4-45: A light micrograph of lampbrush chromosomes in an amphibian oocyte — micrograph showing the extended meiotic chromosomes of a vertebrate oocyte with thousands of lateral loops emanating from the chromosomal axis, representing actively transcribed chromatin domains; illustrates the structural flexibility of chromosomes.
- Figure 4-46: The structure of lampbrush chromosomes — (A) model of paired sister chromatids with loops of extended, transcriptionally active chromatin and a condensed axial region; (B) merged fluorescence micrographs of axolotl lampbrush chromosomes with active loops (RNA pol II, red) and inactive condensed regions (5-methylcytosine, green).
- Figure 4-47: The entire set of polytene chromosomes in one Drosophila salivary cell — drawing of the giant polytene chromosomes with characteristic alternating dark bands and light interbands; all four chromosome pairs aligned in register, linked by a chromocenter of heterochromatin; ~3,700 bands correspond to ~14,000 genes.
- Figure 4-48: Micrographs of polytene chromosomes from Drosophila salivary glands — (A) light micrograph showing fluorescently stained bands of concentrated DNA; (B) electron micrograph showing bands of varying thickness separated by less-condensed interbands.
- Figure 4-49: RNA synthesis in polytene chromosome puffs — autoradiograph showing a decondensed puff region of a Chironomus polytene chromosome labeled with ³H-uridine, demonstrating that chromatin loops expand and become active in transcription as specific genes are expressed during development.
- Figure 4-50: Simultaneous visualization of the chromosome territories for all human chromosomes in a single interphase nucleus — 3D chromosome painting reconstruction showing each chromosome occupies a discrete nuclear territory; homologous chromosomes are not co-localized; demonstrates that interphase chromosomes are not randomly tangled.
- Figure 4-51: The looping out of gene-rich regions of the genome from chromosome territories — fluorescence micrograph of a mouse nucleus with one chromosome painted green and its gene-rich regions stained red, showing that active loci extend outward from the chromosome territory into the nucleoplasm.
- Figure 4-52: A large gene forms a highly extended chromosome loop when highly expressed — fluorescence images comparing (A) inactive thyroglobulin gene locus (compact dot) and (B) active locus in a thyroid cell (extended loop), illustrating that active transcription of large genes unfolds the chromatin into a detectable loop structure.
- Figure 4-53: Use of Hi-C to determine the frequency with which any two DNA sequences are adjacent to each other in a nucleus — diagram of the Hi-C protocol: crosslinking, restriction digestion, biotin-end labeling, proximity ligation, and sequencing; the resulting contact frequency matrix reveals chromosome territories, compartments, and TADs.
- Figure 4-54: Chromosome capture experiment showing topologically associating domains (TADs) — Hi-C contact frequency heatmap of a region of the human genome showing TADs as triangular blocks of high self-interaction; CTCF-bound boundaries separate domains; illustrates loops-within-loops organization.
- Figure 4-55: SMC protein complex formation — structure of cohesin and condensin SMC complexes: long coiled-coil arms joined at a flexible hinge region, with ATP-binding head domains; accessory subunits form the kleisin bridge; illustrates the ring-like architecture that can encircle DNA.
- Figure 4-56: How moving SMC-containing complexes create chromosome loops by extrusion — diagram showing bacterial SMC using ATP hydrolysis to travel along a chromosome from the origin to the terminus, extruding a DNA loop and partitioning the two daughter chromosomes; proposed inchworm mechanism.
- Figure 4-57: Moving cohesin rings divide eukaryotic interphase chromosomes into a long series of looped domains — (A) cohesin loaded onto chromatin enlarges a loop by ATP-driven extrusion until it encounters CTCF boundary proteins; (B) schematic of an interphase chromosome organized as a series of CTCF-anchored cohesin loops.
- Figure 4-58: The distribution of heterochromatin and euchromatin in an interphase nucleus — (A) immunofluorescence of a mouse fibroblast showing H3K9me3 heterochromatin (red) concentrated near the nuclear periphery, H3K27me3 heterochromatin (green) interior to that, and H3K4me3 active euchromatin (blue) in the nuclear interior; (B) polymer modeling explaining the normal and inverted rod-cell arrangement.
- Figure 4-59: A model for the compaction and clustering of heterochromatin through fluctuating weak associations that drive phase separation — illustration showing HP1 protein and deformed nucleosomes forming many weak contacts that collectively drive phase separation of heterochromatin into condensed domains at the nuclear periphery.
- Figure 4-60: A scanning electron micrograph of a region near one end of a typical mitotic chromosome — SEM image showing the knobbly surface of a metaphase chromatid; each knob represents the tip of a looped chromatin domain, and the two paired sister chromatids are clearly distinguished.
- Figure 4-61: How chromosomes fold in M phase — diagram of mitotic chromosome condensation: cohesin loops are replaced by condensin II mega-loops organized around a chromosome axis, then condensin I creates smaller loops within the mega-loops; topoisomerase II decatenates the sister chromatids to produce the final compact metaphase chromosome.
- Figure 4-62: Chromosome organization showing levels of chromatin packaging — hierarchical diagram from DNA double helix (2 nm) → nucleosomes/beads-on-a-string (11 nm) → nucleosome fiber (30 nm) → chromatin loops (700 nm) → metaphase chromatid (1400 nm); shows 10,000-fold net compaction.
- Figure 4-63: A representation of the nucleotide sequence content of the human genome — bar chart showing the proportions of LINEs, SINEs, retroviral elements, DNA-only transposons (together ~45% of the genome), simple repeats, segmental duplications, introns, protein-coding exons, and non-repetitive non-coding DNA; illustrates the "junk DNA" landscape.
- Figure 4-64: A phylogenetic tree showing the relationship between humans and the great apes based on nucleotide sequence data — cladogram with branch lengths proportional to sequence divergence; humans and chimpanzees share a last common ancestor ~6 Ma; human–chimp pairwise divergence ~1.2%; all lineages have diverged ~1.5% from the common ancestor.
- Figure 4-65: Tracing the ancestral sequence from human and chimpanzee leptin genes — aligned 300-nucleotide coding sequences of human and chimpanzee leptin showing only 5 of 441 nucleotide differences; gorilla sequence used as outgroup to infer the ancestral state at each variant site; illustrates parsimony-based ancestral sequence reconstruction.
- Figure 4-66: The very different rates of molecular evolution in different parts of the genome — diagram or plot showing that mitochondrial DNA evolves rapidly (useful for recent divergences like Neanderthals), whereas ribosomal RNA genes evolve slowly (useful for deep divergences like bacteria vs. eukaryotes); the "molecular clock" concept.
- Figure 4-67: A mammalian phylogenetic tree based on genome sequences — broad mammalian phylogeny (including primates, rodents, ungulates, marsupials, monotremes) with divergence times derived from DNA sequence data; rodent lineages show unusually fast molecular clocks.
- Figure 4-68: Synteny between human and mouse chromosomes — ideogram of all 23 human chromosomes colored by syntenic regions corresponding to each of 19 mouse chromosomes; illustrates that ~180 chromosome breakage-and-rejoining events have rearranged conserved gene blocks during ~90 million years of independent evolution.
- Figure 4-69: Comparison of a syntenic portion of mouse and human genomes — alignment of human chromosome 14 and mouse chromosome 12 showing identical gene order (conserved index sequences, red marks) with interspersed net DNA loss in the mouse lineage, explaining the 14% smaller mouse genome.
- Figure 4-70: A comparison of the β-globin gene cluster in human and mouse, showing the locations of transposable elements — diagram showing 5 human β-globin–like genes versus 4 mouse genes; positions of human Alu (green circles) and L1 (red circles) elements; mouse B1 and L1 elements in different positions; transposons are absent from the functional gene sequences due to purifying selection.
- Figure 4-71: Two fish with very different genome sizes — photographs of (A) puffer fish Fugu rubripes (0.4 Gb genome, compact due to reduced transposons and short introns) and (B) West African lungfish Protopterus annectens (>100 Gb genome, swollen with transposons); illustrates the balance between DNA addition and loss driving genome size evolution.
- Figure 4-72: Comparison of the genomic sequences of the human and Fugu huntingtin genes — alignment showing both genes have 67 exons in 1:1 correspondence (connected by curved lines), but the human gene is 7.5× larger (180 kb vs. 24 kb); size difference is entirely due to larger human introns containing retrotransposons (green lines) absent from Fugu.
- Figure 4-73: The types of changes in gene regulation inferred to have predominated during vertebrate evolution — timeline bar chart showing that early vertebrate evolution saw novel regulatory elements near development/transcription-factor genes; later evolution added regulatory elements near receptor genes; most recently, regulatory innovations concentrated near post-translational protein-modification genes (e.g., kinases).
- Figure 4-74: A comparison of the structure of one-chain and four-chain globins — ribbon structures of monomeric globin (from primitive vertebrates) and the α₂β₂ tetrameric hemoglobin; illustrates how gene duplication and divergence created the cooperative oxygen-binding mechanism of tetrameric hemoglobin.
- Figure 4-75: An evolutionary scheme for the globin gene family — phylogenetic tree showing successive gene duplications from a single ancestral globin: first the α/β split (~500 Ma), then the β-globin family expansions (ε, γ, δ, β in mammals), and a chromosome translocation separating α and β clusters onto different chromosomes in birds and mammals.
- Figure 4-76: Schematic view of an antibody (immunoglobulin) molecule — diagram of two identical heavy chains (four Ig domains each) and two light chains (two Ig domains each); all domains encoded by separate exons derived by serial duplication of a single ancestral exon, illustrating exon-shuffling and domain duplication in protein evolution.
- Figure 4-77: How founder effects can determine the set of genetic variants in a population — diagram showing how a catastrophic population bottleneck allows a rare (even mildly deleterious) allele carried by survivors to reach high frequency in the new founder population, explaining the elevated disease allele frequencies in isolated communities.
- Figure 4-78: Tracing the course of human history by analyses of genome sequences — geographic map showing the migration of modern humans out of Africa (~200,000 ya), interbreeding with Neanderthals (~60,000 ya), and the presence of 1–2% Neanderthal DNA in non-African modern human genomes, illustrating how genome sequence comparisons illuminate ancient human population history.
